'''Whitehead's trogon''' ('''''Harpactes whiteheadi''''') is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Trogonidae]]. It is endemic to the island of [[Borneo]], where it is an uncommon {{birdgloss|resident}} in [[primary forest|primary]] mountain forest. One of Borneo's largest trogons at {{convert|29|to|33|cm|abbr=on}} long, it is [[sexually dimorphic]]. The male is crimson on the head, {{birdgloss|nape}}, and underparts, with a black throat and grey chest; the rest of his {{birdgloss|upperparts}} are cinnamon-coloured. The female is similarly patterned, but cinnamon-brown where the male is scarlet. The species was first described for science by [[Richard Bowdler Sharpe]] in 1888, who named it for British explorer and collector [[John Whitehead (explorer)|John Whitehead]]. There are no subspecies.

It is primarily an [[insectivore]], but also eats various plant materials, including fruits and seeds. Other than the timing of its breeding—typically between April and June—little is known about its breeding biology. The [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] rates Whitehead's trogon as a [[near-threatened species]]. While its population numbers have not been quantified, the trogon is thought to be declining. [[Habitat destruction|Habitat loss]] is a key threat.

==Taxonomy and etymology==
English ornithologist Richard Bowdler Sharpe first [[scientific description|described]] Whitehead's trogon for science in 1888, using a specimen collected on [[Mount Kinabalu]], in the Malaysian state of [[Sabah]].{{sfn|Sharpe|1888|p=395}} He gave it the scientific name ''[[Harpactes]] whiteheadi'', assigning it to the genus containing other Asian trogons.{{sfn|Sharpe|1888|p=395}} There are no subspecies.{{sfn|Myers|2016|p=176}} Molecular studies indicate that it is most closely related to the [[Philippine trogon]].{{sfn|Hosner|Sheldon|Lim|Moyle|2010|p=1222}}

The genus name ''Harpactes'' is a transcription of the [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] word ''harpaktes'', meaning "robber".{{sfn|Jobling|2010|p=186}} The [[specific name (zoology)|species]] and common names honor the British explorer [[John Whitehead (explorer)|John Whitehead]], who first collected the bird.{{sfn|Beolens|Watkins|2003|p=365}}

==Description==
[[File:Whitehead's Trogon 0A2A6014.jpg|thumb|Male]]
Like most trogons, Whitehead's trogon is [[sexually dimorphic]]; the male is considerably more colorful than the female.{{sfn|Phillipps|Phillipps|2014|p=188}} It ranks among Borneo's largest trogons, measuring {{convert|29|to|33|cm|abbr=on}} in length.{{#tag:ref|By convention, length is measured from the tip of the bill to the tip of the tail on a dead bird (or skin) laid on its back.{{sfn|Cramp|1977|p=3}} |group="nb"}}{{sfn|Myers|2016|p=176}}{{sfn|Collar|2001|p=109}} The male is crimson on the forehead, crown, nape, and sides of the head, with bare blue skin around the eyes. The rest of his upperparts are cinnamon-brown. His throat is black, shading into a grey breast, but the rest of his underparts are crimson.{{sfn|Collar|2001|p=109}} His wings are primarily black, with fine white barring on the {{birdgloss|secondaries}} and {{birdgloss|coverts}}.{{sfn|Sharpe|1888|p=395}} His tail is mostly white underneath; above, the two central tail feathers are cinnamon with a broad black tip, and the remaining tail feathers are primarily black. The outermost tail feathers are white on the terminal half and along the outer web.{{sfn|Sharpe|1888|p=395}} He has a blue [[beak]], pinkish-brown legs and feet, and reddish-brown [[iris (anatomy)|irises]].{{sfn|Collar|2001|p=109}}{{sfn|Sharpe|1888|p=395}} The female is similarly patterned, but duller, with cinnamon-brown replacing the crimson of the male.{{sfn|Myers|2016|p=176}} The barring on her secondaries and wing coverts is cinnamon-brown rather than white.{{sfn|Sharpe|1888|p=396}} The immature female is similar to the adult female, but her entire ventral side is uniformly coloured, lacking the adult's black throat and grey upper breast. She also has less blue coloring on her beak.{{sfn|van Els|Chua|Burner|Rahman|2016|p=76}} 

===Voice===
{{birdsong|url=https://www.xeno-canto.org/species/Harpactes-whiteheadi|species=Whitehead's trogon}}
Whitehead's trogon [[bird vocalization|vocalises]] only rarely. Its song is a loud series of four to five harsh, slow notes, evenly pitched and variously transcribed as "''kwau kwau kwau kwau''", "''wark wark wark wark''", or "''poop poop poop poop''".{{sfn|Myers|2016|p=176}}{{sfn|Phillipps|Phillipps|2014|p=188}}{{sfn|Collar|2001|p=109}} It also has a rolling "''burr''" call, which is sometimes followed by a loud, descending "''kekekeke''".{{sfn|Myers|2016|p=176}}{{sfn|Collar|2001|p=109}}

==Distribution and habitat==
Whitehead's trogon is [[endemic]] to the island of [[Borneo]], where it occurs in mountainous areas between {{convert|900|and|2000|m}} in elevation.{{sfn|Myers|2016|p=176}} Restricted to [[primary forest]], it favours damp valleys.{{sfn|Phillipps|Phillipps|2014|p=188}} It is an uncommon and poorly-known {{birdgloss|resident}} species.{{sfn|Sheldon|Moyle|Kennard|2001|p=153}}

==Behaviour==
A shy and unobtrusive bird, Whitehead's trogon is easy to overlook as it sits quietly in the upper storey of dense forest. It is {{birdgloss|resident}} where it occurs. It associates loosely with [[mixed species flock]]s containing [[chestnut-hooded laughingthrush|chestnut-hooded]] and [[Sunda laughingthrush]]es, [[Whitehead's broadbill]]s and [[Sunda cuckooshrike]]s.{{sfn|van Els|Chua|Burner|Rahman|2016|p=76}} 

===Feeding===
Like all trogons, Whitehead's trogon feeds primarily on insects, which it captures in [[sallying]] flight from a perch, or [[gleaning (birds)|gleans]] from foliage.{{sfn|Phillipps|Phillipps|2014|p=188}} Most of this prey is fairly large, including [[grasshopper]]s, [[locust]]s, [[stick insect]]s, and [[leaf insect]]s; however, insects as small as [[ant]]s are taken.{{sfn|Collar|2001|p=109}} It also eats fruit, seeds and other plant material.{{sfn|Phillipps|Phillipps|2014|p=188}}{{sfn|van Els|Chua|Burner|Rahman|2016|p=77}} Though it generally perches just under the canopy, it typically hunts in the understorey.{{sfn|Myers|2016|p=176}}{{sfn|Phillipps|Phillipps|2014|p=188}} In the mixed flocks it accompanies, it usually hunts at lower levels than the other species do.{{sfn|van Els|Chua|Burner|Rahman|2016|p=76}} Individuals have been found with [[gastrolith|stones]] in their stomachs.{{sfn|Collar|2001|p=109}}

===Breeding===
Very little is known about the Whitehead trogon's breeding ecology.{{sfn|Collar|2001|p=109}} Birds have been found in breeding condition in late March and October; the latter date suggests the possibility of multiple broods or geographical variation in the breeding period. Nesting is known to occur in April, young birds have been collected in June, and family groups have been seen together in July.{{sfn|van Els|Chua|Burner|Rahman|2016|pp=77–78}} However, the [[bird nest|nest]] and [[bird egg|eggs]] remain undescribed, and details of its breeding biology—[[egg incubation|incubation]] and nesting periods, size of [[clutch (eggs)|clutch]], length of time to [[fledging]], division of nestling care, and so forth—are not known.{{sfn|Collar|2001|p=109}}

==Conservation==
The [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] has rated Whitehead's trogon as a [[near-threatened species]]. Although its population has not been quantified, it is thought to be decreasing. Habitat loss, both through logging and conversion to agricultural use, is occurring at lower elevations on some of mountains where it lives.{{sfn|BirdLife International|2016}}

